		<text id="22" type="text/plain" rect="(1200.0, 886.6666666666665, 210.0, 298.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">Confusion matrix:

-- Random Forest --
percentage of predicted correct:

Hacking: 48%
Improper disposal: 33.3%
Loss: 21.1%
Theft: 68.8%
unauthorized access: 28.8%
Other: 16.7%
</text>
		<text id="23" type="text/plain" rect="(1226.6666666666665, 1273.333333333333, 206.66666666666652, 342.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">Confusion matrix:

-- Logistic regression  --
percenatge of predicted correct:

hacking: 57.1%
improper disposal: 50%
loss: 50%
theft: 69.5%
unauthorized access: 41%
other: 25%</text>
		<text id="24" type="text/plain" rect="(34.99999999999994, 1334.9999999999995, 150.0, 122.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">discretize the "individuals affected" to natural binning (2 desired bins)</text>
		<text id="25" type="text/plain" rect="(275.0, 1439.9999999999995, 150.0, 56.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">preprocess with intervals (-1,1)</text>
		<text id="26" type="text/plain" rect="(414.9999999999999, 1451.6666666666665, 150.0, 100.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">Seperate the data to 70% training and 30% sample data</text>
		<text id="27" type="text/plain" rect="(625.0000000000001, 1593.3333333333335, 150.0, 100.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">Use SVM, Logisitic regression, and random forest as ML models</text>
		<text id="28" type="text/plain" rect="(1433.3333333333337, 1200.0, 266.66666666666674, 496.0)" font-family="Segoe UI" font-size="16">-- CONCLUSION --

Out of all of the training models, using "edit domain" and "discretize" widget gives the best result

Since the "location of breached information" and type of breach" data is messy, we need to clean it by merging the minor datas together to make prediction process better

However, the data is too small (with 1000 instances), we would need more data to create a more accurate prediction

</text>
	</annotations>
